The SIMP (Solid Isotropic Material with Penalization) method is commonly used, where a density variable (ranging from 0 to 1) represents the material presence at each point in the discretized domain. The optimization iteratively updates these densities based on sensitivity analysis (calculating the derivative of compliance with respect to density) and a gradient-based optimization algorithm (e.g., the method of moving asymptotes, MMA). The volume constraint ensures that the total material used remains within the specified fraction of the design domain.
